A U.S. crony capitalism
Do you remember the East Asian crisis? When the U.S. Treasury and its IMF allies shifted the blame for the problems in this region onto crony capitalism, lack of transparency, and ineffective governance?
Countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting audit firms, and to introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their businesses.
It doesn't matter that under the authority of its own entrepreneurs, East Asia has developed more rapidly than any other region—and with greater stability—over the past three decades.
The growing scandal of Enron gives a new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "You must be perfect to criticize others."
Enron used large accounting schemes and complicated financial products (derivatives) to mislead investors about its value.
No transparency here.
She used her money to gain influence and power, shape U.S. energy policy, and escape regulations.
Patronage capitalism is not new, nor is it exclusive to a single party.
The former U.S. Treasury Secretary, Robert Rubin, allegedly tried to influence the current government to intervene on Enron's behalf in the controversial dispute in India.
When he was in office, he intervened when the accounting standards-setting body, supposedly independent, attempted to clean up the accounting of top executives' compensation.
It is partly because of him that this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent has been hindered.
The enthusiasm of the United States to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free markets is merely a thin veil for the benefit of the old companies: giving favors to those who have the right connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and the problems were not revealed demonstrates the absence of crony capitalism.
My interpretation is different: it shows the importance of a free press that may not stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to focus on Enron, the number of Congress members who had accepted money from Enron was disclosed.
Contributions to the campaigns were not merely matters of public interest, but constituted an investment.
Like most Enron investments, everything went smoothly in the short term, but did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons can be learned from this venture.
Some regarding politics: the Enron scandal strengthens the arguments in favor of campaign financing reform and the necessity of even more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
Democracies are undermined by business interests that are actually capable of buying elections.
The Bush administration nevertheless refuses to disclose information that would attest to the role of corporate interests in shaping its energy policy.
Other lessons cover economics, more specifically, the economics of information.
For markets to function, for the appropriate signals that efficiently allocate resources to be provided, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as positive an image as possible.
Account control is intended to place limits on potential abuses.
But who will guard the guards?
Who will control the account controllers?
We count greatly on motivations.
The auditors wish to preserve their reputation.
But the relationship between advisory practices and account control leads to other perverse motivations: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within audit firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of the audits could be compromised.
He is undoubtedly the forgotten hero of the debacle.
But accounting firms and their corporate clients — which is hardly surprising, given the conspiracy that has developed — strongly attacked his proposal to separate advisory activities from accounting control functions.
What Levitt understood—and what the Enron collapse so clearly demonstrated—is that motivations are important, but that unregulated markets cannot on their own provide the best motivations.
Markets cannot provide motivations for the creation of wealth; they can provide motivations for the type of schemes that Enron implemented.
The new economy — and its complex new financial instruments — highlight the problems with reliable accounting control structures; they make them easier to obscure.
Rather than facing the problems, the corporate America systematically turns its back on them, supported and encouraged by the American crony capitalism.
The major problem of our time is to find the right balance between government and the market.
The status quo will assert that Enron is an exception: that its downfall was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud, and that those who violate these laws must face the consequences and will face them.
But the majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its auditors state that its central practices complied with the law and that thousands of companies act in the same way.
They're right - and that's precisely the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information received adequately reflects the economic situation of a company.
Within the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors have no possibility of being offered these guarantees at the present time.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check the motives.
We can try to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot rely on them when so many people around the world say nothing about the phenomenon of the " revolving door ".
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we observe that they manage them in their own interests.
But even when evidence of such abuse becomes evident, new places for abuse are repeatedly created—take, for example, the U.S. repeal of the Glass-Steagall Act, which separated commercial from investment banking.
We have repeatedly observed the consequences of the excesses of unregulated market liberalization.
We must now resist the temptation to lean toward the other extreme.
The challenge is to achieve the right balance.
